<DOC><DOCNO> AP890714-0130 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-14-89 1422EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Somalia     07-14 0370</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Somalia,0384</SECOND><HEAD>Eight Civilians and Troops Killed in Shooting Outside Somali Mosque</HEAD><DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Troops opened fire Friday on worshipersoutside a mosque in Mogadishu, the Somali capital, and state radioreported eight people were killed in what the government calledreligious disturbances.   A resident said it appeared troops opened fire as Moslems lefttheir place of prayer during Eid al-Adha, the three-day Feast ofSacrifice that is Islam's holiest celebration.   The resident, who spoke on condition he not be identifiedfurther, said gunfire erupted around midday and continuedsporadically through the afternoon. He said most of the shootingappeared to be around a mosque in a western neighborhood.   The shootings come in a week of unconfirmed reports thatauthorities have detained several Moslem religious leaders.   A Ministry of the Interior statement broadcast on state radiosaid a group of ``troublemakers masquerading behind the cloak ofreligion'' started the disturbances in Hodhan neighborhood.   The report, monitored in Nairobi, said security forces werecalled out to curb the disturbances but the ``troublemakers refusedto disperse peacefully.''   Fighting broke out and eight people were killed and 24 wereinjured, according to the statement. The dead included``troublemakers'' and members of the security forces, it said.   The resident said the government imposed a 6 p.m. to 6 a.m.curfew in the capital.   He said he saw little activity during an afternoon drive throughMogadishu, except for two soldiers guarding an army post.   ``However, people in the neighborhood say they've heard gunfireall around,'' he said.   On Sunday, an unidentified gunman shot and killed Mogadishu'sRoman Catholic Bishop Salvatore Pietro Colombo. It was not knownwhether Friday's disturbances were related.   This East African nation on the Indian Ocean has been led since1969 by the autocratic President Siad Barre, who allows noopposition to his rule. It is difficult to get news from the country.   Since 1981, the government has battled the Somali NationalMovement, a northern insurgency that demands Barre's removal.Intensified fighting between the rebels and the government the past18 months has driven more than 200,000 Somalis into refugee camps inneighboring Ethiopia.   The impoverished nation is overwhelmingly pastoral and most ofthe 9 million people are Moslem.</TEXT></DOC>